<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF109-713-739  </DOCNO><DOCID>09 713 739.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Electronic Engineering Times  Dec 17 1990 n621 p64(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>High-level languages take off. (part of the annual report onproduct trends)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Weiss, Ray.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>1990 saw increased acceptance of high-level programming languagessuch as C and C++ for embedded systems and the introduction of anumber of development tools and compilers.andP;  C programming isbecoming a mainstay of the 8-bit microprocessor andmicrocontroller sector.andP;  Metalink released a software tool for Cthat features a source-code debug tool.andP;  C compilers wereintroduced by Franklin Software, Archimedes Software and ByteCraft.andP;  Outstanding introductions for C++ included SaberSoftware's Saber C++ development environment and BorlandInternational's Turbo C++.andP;  Sun Microsystems and Hewlett-Packardhave applied C++ to workstations.andP;  Smalltalk, the first commercialobject-oriented programming system (OOPS), continues to gainground and garner support.andP;  Smalltalk's strongest selling point isits portability.andP;  Elsewhere in the OOPS arena, Digital EquipmentCorp introduced Trellis, a programming language that supportsmultiple inheritance, with a strict compile-time-type checking.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   MetaLink Software (Product development)Digital Equipment Corp. (Product development)Saber Software Inc. (Product development)Borland International Inc. (Product development)Byte Craft Ltd. (Product development).andO;Ticker:    DEC.andO;Topic:     TrendsOutlookReview of Past YearProgramming LanguagesC Programming LanguageObject-Oriented LanguagesProduct Development.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>